                        <desc>Large, legible Nasta’liq. Black ink. Red ink used to mark names of poetic forms and poets.</desc>
                        <persName key="person_f4275">Umīd Rāy</persName>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <list>
                        <item>
                           <p>
                              <label>Marginalia <locus>f. 206a</locus>
                              </label> A marginal note on the orginal from which this copy was made.</p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                           <p>
                              <locus>Inside covers</locus>: pasted print descriptions of the work from a sale catalogue, for "407. Daulet Shah" and "278... Tezkir Shoara". Numbered 130 and later 404.</p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                           <p>
                              <locus>Inside covers</locus> Binder's ticket: "Bound by R. Macculloch No 143 Mirzapore Calcutta"</p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                           <p>
                              <label>Marginalia <locus>f.ixa</locus>
                              </label> Inscribed "D. Woodburn".</p>
                        </item>
                     </list>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <p>Binding by <persName key="person_f3538">Robert MacCulloch</persName>. Morocco leather on wood. Tooled and gilded. Stitched. Gilt gauffered fore-edge.</p>
                     <p>For further information on the binder see <bibl>Morris, John. "A Binding by Robert MacCulloch, Calcutta 1834." <title>The Book Collector</title> 42. 3 (Autumn 1993), 396-8</bibl>
                     </p>
                     <decoNote type="illustration"/>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1783">1196 A.H.</origDate>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Copied for Captain James Dunn (either Colonel James Dunn, d 1816 or Major James Dunn, d 1824).</p>
                     <p>Inscribed "D. Woodburn". This could either be <persName key="person_f874">David Woodburn (1805-1888)</persName> who was in the Bengal Medical Service 1827-1856, or <persName key="person_f873">David Woodburn (1745-1804)</persName>, a colonel in the Bengal Army.</p>
                     <p>Bound in Kolkata by <persName key="person_f3538">Robert MacCulloch</persName>, fl. 1827-1834.</p>
                     <p>Formerly owned by <persName type="standard" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/76440932" key="person_76440932">William Cureton (1808-1864)</persName>, whose signature is found on the end papers.</p>
                     <p>Formerly part of the collection of the Persian scholar <persName type="standard" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/#Bland,_Nathaniel,_1803-1865" key="person_20108923">Nathaniel Bland (1803-1865)</persName>. Bland’s oriental manuscripts were sold through Bernard Quaritch in 1866 to <persName type="standard" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/#Crawford,_Alexander_Crawford_Lindsay,_Earl_of,_1812-1880" key="person_97751058">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford</persName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Purchased by Mrs Enriqueta Rylands, on behalf of the John Rylands Library, in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName type="standard" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/#Crawford,_James_Ludovic_Lindsay,_Earl_of,_1847-1913" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford</persName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
